04829nam a22005775i 9780822389538DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20072007ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a2009280159  a97808223895387 a10.1515/97808223895382doi  a(DE-B1597)554484  a(OCoLC)1055307561  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC00aGN635.I65bB654 2007b 4aGN635.I65bB654 2007 7aSOC0020102bisacsh1 aBoellstorff, Tom, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Coincidence of Desires :bAnthropology, Queer Studies, Indonesia /cTom Boellstorff. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2007] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (292 p.) :b19 illustrations, 7 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 ae-Duke books scholarly collection00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tA Note on Indonesian Terms and Italicization -- tIntroduction: Queering disciplines in time -- tOne. Zines and zones of desire -- tTwo. Warias, national transvestites -- tThree. Gay language, registering belonging -- tFour. Between religion and desire -- tFive. The emergence of political homophobia -- tSix. Comparatively queer in southeast Asia -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn A Coincidence of Desires, Tom Boellstorff considers how interdisciplinary collaboration between anthropology and queer studies might enrich both fields. For more than a decade he has visited Indonesia, both as an anthropologist exploring gender and sexuality and as an activist involved in HIV prevention work. Drawing on these experiences, he provides several in-depth case studies, primarily concerning the lives of Indonesian men who term themselves gay (an Indonesian-language word that overlaps with, but does not correspond exactly to, the English word "gay"). These case studies put interdisciplinary research approaches into practice. They are preceded and followed by theoretical meditations on the most productive forms that collaborations between queer studies and anthropology might take. Boellstorff uses theories of time to ask how a model of "coincidence" might open up new possibilities for cooperation between the two disciplines. He also juxtaposes his own work with other scholars' studies of Indonesia, Thailand, the Philippines, Malaysia, and Singapore to compare queer sexualities across Southeast Asia. In doing so, he asks how comparison might be understood as a queer project and how queerness might be understood as comparative.The case studies contained in A Coincidence of Desires speak to questions about the relation of sexualities to nationalism, religion, and globalization. They include an examination of zines published by gay Indonesians; an analysis of bahasa gay-a slang spoken by gay Indonesians that is increasingly appropriated in Indonesian popular culture; and an exploration of the place of warias (roughly, "male-to-female transvestites") within Indonesian society. Boellstorff also considers the tension between Islam and sexuality in gay Indonesians' lives and a series of incidents in which groups of men, identified with Islamic fundamentalism, violently attacked gatherings of gay men. Collectively, these studies insist on the primacy of empirical investigation to any queer studies project that wishes to speak to the specificities of lived experience.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aEthnologyzIndonesia. 0aGay menzIndonesiaxSocial conditions. 0aMale homosexualityzIndonesia. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822389538zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gru